value.value: MtrR is a repressor of mtrCDE efflux pump expression, point mutations in mtrR confer resistance to azithromycin and other drugs.

label.value: Mycobacterium tuberculosis 16S rRNA mutation conferring resistance to capreomycin

value.value: Point mutations in the 3' domain of 16S rRNA of Mycobacterium tuberculosis can confer resistance to capreomycin.
A CMY-2-like beta-lactamase which confers resistance to cephalosporin antibiotics, and is also capable of hydrolyzing the CMY-2 inhibitors ticarcillin and cloxacillin.
SCOs are Class A beta-lactamases that confer resistance to a narrow range of penams, with some minor activity on cephalosporins and carbapenems.

Narrow-spectrum beta-lactamase isolated from several Acinetobacter spp. isolates from Argentina, as well as E. Coli. Hydrolyzes penicillins at a high level and cephalosporins and carbapenems at a very low level.

label.value: inhA with mutations with conferring resistance to ethionamide

definition.value: Genes with mutations in inhA which confer resistance to ethionamide class antibiotics.

label.value: Mycobacterium tuberculosis inhA mutations conferring resistance to ethionamide

value.value: inhA is a enoyl-acyl carrier reductase used in lipid metabolism and farry acid biosynthesis. It is inhibited by ethionamide. Mutations in the promoter region or multiple copies of the inhA show marked resistance to ethionamide mediated inhibition of mycolic acid biosynthesis.

definition.value: Mutations that occur in the clp protease subunit clpC1 that increases resistance to antibiotics.

clpC1 is a subunit of the clp protease that is ATP-dependent. It functions to direct the clp protease to specific substrates. In the presence of ATP it hydrolyses proteins and may be involved in the degradation of denatured proteins.
Mutations that occur in gpsI that increases resistance to antibiotics.

gpsI codes for polyribonucleotide nucleotidyltransferase which is a protein involved in mRNA degradation. It catalyzes the phosphorolysis of single-stranded polyribonucleotides in the 3'- to 5'-direction.
Mutations that occur in the mas that increases resistance to antibiotics.

Mas is a multifunctional mycocerosic acid synthase membrane-associated mas. It catalyzes the elongation of N-fatty acyl-CoA with methylamalonyl-CoA as the elongating agent to form mycocerosyl fatty acids present in mycobacterium.
Mutations that occur in the ppsC that increases resistance to antibiotics.

ppsC codes for the phthiocerol synthesis polyketide synthase type 1. It is involved in the elongation of C22-24 fatty acids by the addition of methylmalonyl-CoA extender units to yield phthiocerol derivatives in a complete reduction. Research has pointed towards this protein to be a high confidence drug target.
Mutations that occur in the ppsD that increases resistance to antibiotics.

ppsD codes for the phthiocerol synthesis polyketide synthase type 1. It is involved in the elongation of C22-24 fatty acids by the addition of malonyl-CoA extender units to yield phthiocerol derivatives in a partial reduction.
Mutations that occur in the fabg1 gene resulting in the inability for the antibiotic to inhibit mycolic acid biosynthesis.
fabG1 is involved in the fatty acid synthesis pathway, acting in the first reduction step for mycolic acid. It is associated with ethionamide resistance.
Mutations that occur on the mshC gene resulting in the inability for antibiotic to function.
